    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\underline {\mathrm {data} }}\;\left({\frac {}{{\mathsf {Nat}}:\star }}\right)\;{\underline {\mathrm {where} }}\;\left({\frac {}{{\mathsf {zero}}:{\mathsf {Nat}}}}\right)\;;\;\left({\frac {n:{\mathsf {Nat}}}{{\mathsf {suc}}\ n:{\mathsf {Nat}}}}\right)}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/8f7debd56501088fecac0bcfd1abde05e5f7ecbe" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -2.505ex; width:55.421ex; height:6.176ex;" alt="{\underline {\mathrm {data} }}\;\left({\frac {}{{\mathsf {Nat}}:\star }}\right)\;{\underline {\mathrm {where} }}\;\left({\frac {}{{\mathsf {zero}}:{\mathsf {Nat}}}}\right)\;;\;\left({\frac {n:{\mathsf {Nat}}}{{\mathsf {suc}}\ n:{\mathsf {Nat}}}}\right)" /></span></p>
<p>The horizontal-line notation can be read as "assuming (what is on the top) is true, we can infer that (what is on the bottom) is true." For example, "assuming <code>n</code> is of type <code>Nat</code>, then <code>suc n</code> is of type <code>Nat</code>." If nothing is on the top, then the bottom statement is always true: "<code>zero</code> is of type <code>Nat</code> (in all cases)."</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Recursion_on_naturals">Recursion on naturals</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Epigram_(programming_language)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Recursion on naturals">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
